// TEST: exec_core_error
// EXPECT: output "boom;again: boom"
//
// THE PAYOFF FIXTURE for `core.error`: a user program that `use`s the embedded
// `core.error` stdlib module, constructs a `SimpleError` via the `error(...)`
// constructor, and reads its message back through the `message()` method —
// compiled + run on ALL FIVE targets (no `// EXPECT: targets` restriction).
//
// FIELD/METHOD NAME-COLLISION LOCK (all 5). `core.error` declares `record
// SimpleError { message: String }` *and* `fn message(self) -> String` (the
// `Error` trait method). Bock keeps a field (`self.message`) and a method
// (`self.message()`) distinct, but most target object models collapse a field
// and a same-named method onto one member slot. The codegen remedy renames the
// *method* (the field keeps its name) at its declaration and every call site:
//
//   - Go:     `Message` field + method ⇒ `go build` error ("has both field and
//             method named Message"); method emitted as `MessageMethod()`.
//   - TS:     class field + merged-interface method ⇒ "Duplicate identifier";
//             method (trait sig + merged sig + prototype + calls) ⇒ `messageMethod`.
//   - JS:     instance field shadows the prototype method (`e.message()` is "not
//             a function"); method ⇒ `messageMethod`.
//   - Python: `@dataclass` field overwrites the method attribute (`'str' object
//             is not callable`); method ⇒ `message_method`.
//   - Rust:   a field and an inherent method may share a name — a no-op
//             regression guard.
//
// The disambiguation is a shared mechanism: every backend computes the
// collision-renamed method name through `generator::disambiguate_method_name`
// against `generator::collect_record_field_names`, so future field/method pairs
// are handled uniformly. This fixture exercises `core.error.message()` end to
// end (build + run + stdout diff) on every installed toolchain.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale).
module main

use core.error.{SimpleError, error}

fn read(e: SimpleError) -> String {
  e.message()
}

fn main() -> Void {
  let e = error("boom")
  let direct: String = e.message()
  let again: String = read(error("boom"))
  println("${direct};again: ${again}")
}
